<subSubSection id="D792B2C1E04C68321D397D324E834A9F" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="F50674B4E7AEC3A694EC14BB57C72524" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BCF9B2C63812195C0AE6DC513DB00E45" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<taxonomicName id="E95A20CE2EE64FD1A1AAF8231A45904E" authorityName="Schneider, Claps, Wei, Normark &amp; Normark" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Diaspididae" genus="Hemiberlesia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hemiberlesia ozolita" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ozolita">
<emphasis id="19D0FFBC9F46B4D294B0A33100DE596B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Hemiberlesia ozolita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="AE3E3F4437347CEA0601CF6C70150B53" genus="H." lsidName="H. nothofagi" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="nothofagi">
<emphasis id="C53D40CF3FA5A5D0A0DB21FFDF7456FF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">H. nothofagi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Williams, but 
<taxonomicName id="22989953173F001BC17E5FD2010AF5B4" genus="H." lsidName="H. ozolita" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="ozolita">
<emphasis id="5273257A93B04F707E7A078C55FF43E5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">H. ozolita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. is distinctive in having plates in the first space shorter than L1, 3 plates beyond L2, anal opening relatively small (&lt;25 
<normalizedToken id="0C2F2BF8FA2DBC13DCB7643B20189255" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in diameter), 31-42 macroducts on each side of the pygidium, and groups of ventral submarginal microducts running from the pygidium to the thorax. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName id="2FB9B9B438D39E6A7753ABAF6523DDD1" genus="H." lsidName="H. nothofagi" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="nothofagi">
<emphasis id="EC9EA0982F2796B52A87677B479AA7D0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">H. nothofagi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has plates in the first space exceeding L1 in length, 6-7 plates beyond L2, a large anal opening (30 
<normalizedToken id="8AD83CA7042FCADFF90FB5203F09C76C" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in diameter), about 26 pygidial macroducts per side, and few microducts present on the venter, not arranged in submarginal groups on thoracic and pre-pygidial segments. The new species is also similar to 
<taxonomicName id="70A93D48990F76710583BD3109F6342D" genus="H." lsidName="H. rapax" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="rapax">
<emphasis id="F7968B8A3FA2A533ABBDA638A83899E7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">H. rapax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except it has a much smaller anal opening and the pre-pygidial macroducts are longer, about as long as the pygidial macroducts.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AF6A5C910CE037FAE83AFAF57010D458" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<taxonomicName id="7B8701BABD1723DFDFC10CA2919A94C0" authorityName="Schneider, Claps, Wei, Normark &amp; Normark" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Diaspididae" genus="Hemiberlesia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hemiberlesia ozolita" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ozolita">
<emphasis id="7FEA3AAA40FA828AACC3AD8F6265863A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Hemiberlesia ozolita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. constitutes the sister-lineage of a clade that includes all other sampled 
<taxonomicName id="6B49E85D1D72E9631C77BC3077DD3586" authorityName="Cockerell in Leonardi" authorityYear="1897" class="Insecta" family="Diaspididae" genus="Hemiberlesia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hemiberlesia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4E3B7ECE6F1477F7D161D146D74DE61E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Hemiberlesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species and 
<taxonomicName id="02571E9CF1E6830AD5238953F93CFF83" authorityName="Ferris" authorityYear="1941" class="Insecta" family="Diaspididae" genus="Palinaspis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Palinaspis sordidata" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sordidata">
<emphasis id="EACFD359F86E448559440FE8C75D0A40" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Palinaspis sordidata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, according to the phylogenetic estimate of 
<bibRefCitation id="7902C52399F4360ED7B23424B9A30EFA" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2018.09.003" author="Schneider, SA" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" pagination="291 - 303" refId="B21" refString="Schneider, SA, Okusu, A, Normark, BB, 2018. Molecular phylogenetics of Aspidiotini armored scale insects (Hemiptera: Diaspididae) reveals rampant paraphyly, curious species radiations, and multiple origins of association with Melissotarsus ants (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 129: 291 - 303, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2018.09.003" title="Molecular phylogenetics of Aspidiotini armored scale insects (Hemiptera: Diaspididae) reveals rampant paraphyly, curious species radiations, and multiple origins of association with Melissotarsus ants (Hymenoptera: Formicidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2018.09.003" volume="129" year="2018">Schneider et al. (2018)</bibRefCitation>
. The relatively small anal opening in this species is a trait shared in common with several other species formerly placed in 
<taxonomicName id="66363F84BB4FA2BD08C885FE0639744F" authorityName="Balachowsky" authorityYear="1948" class="Insecta" family="Diaspididae" genus="Abgrallaspis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Abgrallaspis" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1BADD86339660548A27396C731F595F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Abgrallaspis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that have since been transferred to 
<taxonomicName id="C263E925767952CBBECAE3393DF744BC" authorityName="Cockerell in Leonardi" authorityYear="1897" class="Insecta" family="Diaspididae" genus="Hemiberlesia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hemiberlesia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E75394C7764FE43A1F6E5D5FA6ABF0A4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Hemiberlesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="B48A3B26923A8E63E58BB2B57EDBCD6B" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1603/AN13110" author="Normark, BB" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Entomological Society of America" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" pagination="37 - 49" refId="B17" refString="Normark, BB, Morse, GE, Krewinski, A, Okusu, A, 2014. Armored scale insects (Hemiptera: Diaspididae) of San Lorenzo National Park, Panama, with descriptions of two new species. Annals of the Entomological Society of America 107: 37 - 49, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1603/AN13110" title="Armored scale insects (Hemiptera: Diaspididae) of San Lorenzo National Park, Panama, with descriptions of two new species." url="https://doi.org/10.1603/AN13110" volume="107" year="2014">Normark et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
), a decision supported by molecular evidence.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5E63372B2FE2E43C03082D4762B9848F" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="host">
<paragraph id="859269D2C2A476F56283E691958AF884" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Host plant.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F153591F05B594E2D9D950CFC5BACB4F" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Not recorded.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="41A3962D7942B2163C95013C975A87E2" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="390F5D2FEA233939A33E8D2E3007C94C" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1B906840047EF312C3CF66B32E125A4A" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
The specific epithet is an adjective formed from the Greek terms 
<emphasis id="232D93BFD4FA15F5662966F0558B070C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">ozotos</emphasis>
, meaning branching, and 
<emphasis id="A1736BEE3C40497EB9B981B322278A2E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">litos</emphasis>
, meaning simple, and is used to describe the distinctly simple pygidial plates of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
